body:
I found some bug (or feature?) of JDT. In this case:

```
class Super {
  int x;
}
class Sub extends Super {
  void foo() {
    System.out.println(x);
  }
}
```

It creates `FieldBinding` for x with declaringClass as `Sub`, not `Super`. This is translated to Spoon, as `CtFieldReference` to `x` has `declaringType` set to `Sub`.

This might lead to different problems, for me, for example, getting declaration didn't work, here how I fixed that:

```
diff --git a/src/main/java/spoon/support/reflect/reference/CtFieldReferenceImpl.java b/src/main/java/spoon/support/reflect/reference/CtFieldReferenceImpl.java
index 074e075..58abe0c 100644
--- a/src/main/java/spoon/support/reflect/reference/CtFieldReferenceImpl.java
+++ b/src/main/java/spoon/support/reflect/reference/CtFieldReferenceImpl.java
@@ -128,11 +128,19 @@ public class CtFieldReferenceImpl<T> extends CtVariableReferenceImpl<T>
        @Override
        @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
        public CtField<T> getDeclaration() {
-               CtType<?> type = (CtType<?>) declaringType.getDeclaration();
-               if ((declaringType != null) && (type != null)) {
-                       return (CtField<T>) type.getField(getSimpleName());
+               CtTypeReference<?> declaringType = this.declaringType;
+               while(true) {
+                       if (declaringType == null)
+                               return null;
+                       CtType<?> type = (CtType<?>) declaringType.getDeclaration();
+                       if (type == null)
+                               return null;
+
+                       CtField<T> field = (CtField<T>) type.getField(getSimpleName());
+                       if (field != null)
+                               return field;
+                       declaringType = declaringType.getSuperclass();
                }
-               return null;
        }

        public CtTypeReference<?> getDeclaringType() {
```
